",["$r","p",null,{"children":["How context works might remind you of ",["$r","a",null,{"href":"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/inheritance","target":"_blank","rel":"nofollow noopener noreferrer","children":"CSS property inheritance."}]," In CSS, you can specify ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"color: blue"}]," for a ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"<div>"}],", and any DOM node inside of it, no matter how deep, will inherit that color unless some other DOM node in the middle overrides it with ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"color: green"}],". Similarly, in React, the only way to override some context coming from above is to wrap children into a context provider with a different value."]}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":["In CSS, different properties like ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"color"}]," and ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"background-color"}]," don’t override each other. You can set all  ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"<div>"}],"’s ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"color"}]," to red without impacting ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"background-color"}],". Similarly, ",["$r","strong",null,{"children":"different React contexts don’t override each other."}]," Each context that you make with ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"createContext()"}]," is completely separate from other ones, and ties together components using and providing ",["$r","em",null,{"children":"that particular"}]," context. One component may use or provide many different contexts without a problem."]}],"
